<br>
<br>
I'm adopted, I was adopted at the age of about two months.  The only request of my birthmother was that I go to an Episcopalian family.  I was raised in a good, conservative, highly liturgical Episcopal church in Massachusetts (what? a conservative Episcopal church in MA??? lol, I think we're one of a VERY small amount...) and I've served the church in every way a lay person under the age of twenty can serve.  I've been a torch bearer, a crucifer, a thurifer, in the choir(s), in the altar guild, helped my mom in the flower guild, helped my mom's administrative duties (mainly stuffing bulletins and mailings), been an officer every year I was in the youth group, leading up to being the president, and last but CERTAINLY not least being a subdeacon.  If any of those terms (subdeacon, crucifer, thurifer, etc) mean anything to you...<br>
<br>
Upon going to college, I had some falling-away issues.  Namely, I didn't have a car, and I didn't really know any Christians, let alone Christians with cars who would take me to church with them.  I attended InterVarsity Christian Fellowship's opening-of-the-year service and put my name on the list, mainly out of habit (church has always been something I did) but nobody from IVCF followed up on that, and I didn't really hear anything about them until VERY late in the year.  Finally, I started getting really interested in this great Mennonite guy and we started going out and therefore I went with him (he had a car! hehe) to church at an interdenominational church with a heart for world missions.  The style of worship was so different and refreshing, and I saw passion in the believers there.  Then of course I started going to large groups with him, and thanks to meeting friends at large group, someone learned which dorm I lived in and bugged me to get involved in the small group Bible studies.<br>
<br>
These were all the things I was used to--Bible studies, and the fun large group stuff that reminded me of my old youth group.  I was rather thankful that I finally got involved with IV and into a church!  But our chapter of IVCF just HAD to do something about the way it followed up on NSO events (new student outreach)--and for that matter all outreach events.<br>
<br>
It's now my third year here.  I've really only been involved with IVCF for about a year, but I'm on the exec team.  It's kinda cool.  I'm psyched about this coming year, and the ways God seems to be headed with the lost on campus.  Most of the people in IVCF would probably be scared by the amount of liturgy at my home church.  But that's one of the things I love most (and miss most) about home--there is so much beautiful tradition.  (Of course, all too often, passion for tradition takes the place of passion for God...but that's another topic...)<br>
<br>
Anyways, I don't know how much longer I'll be an Episcopalian.  Either my parish and others who disagree with recent decisions will split, or I may just become Lutheran and marry this guy (as a friend of mine suggested...I laughed at it, since we're not even going out, but I think my friend was serious...)<br>
<br>
The only problem I had with the local Lutheran church was they didn't let me take communion with them.  *feels left out*  I still have to figure out the reasoning behind that...it might make sense eventually... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jebleez>Jebleez</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sir Jeb,<br>Tone & Rhythm Man</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#B87333>(9/3/03 12:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://killeenroos.com/2/battle2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Denominations: Your history?</span><hr size=1> Hey NS!<br>
Boy did you ask the question about communion in the right place <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
We've got a real-live Lutheran right here <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
This is the Missouri Synod Lutheran Church's stance on the subject, but you'll find the other Lutheran synods have a very similar position:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So it is not that a Lutheran congregation wants to bar fellow-saints from the blessings of the Eucharist when they practice Close Communion. It is not that they want to be separatistic,or set themselves up as judges of other men.The practice of Close Communion is prompted by love and is born of the heartfelt conviction,on the basis of Scripture alone,that we must follow Christ’s command.This means refusing the Lord’s Supper to those whose belief is not known to us. It is not showing love to allow a person to do something harmful,even though he may think it is for his own good. It also means if they are members of a Christian body which departs from the full truth of the Scripture in some of its doctrines, that we must not minimize the evil of this false teaching by opening our fellowship to any and all Christians who err in the faith<br>
Close communion seeks to prevent a profession of confessional unity in faith where there is,in fact,disunity and disagreement. “In keeping with the principle that the celebration and reception of the Lord’s Supper is a confession of the unity of faith, while at the same time recognizing that there will be instances when sensitive pastoral care needs to be exercised, the Synod has established an official practice requiring,‘that pastors and congregations of The Lutheran Church - Missouri Synod,except in situations of emergency and in special cases of pastoral care,commune individuals of only those synods that are now in fellowship with us.By following this practice whereby only those individuals who are members of the Synod or of a church body with which the Synod is in altar and pulpit fellowship are ordinarily communed,pastors and congregations preserve the integrity of their witness to the Gospel of Christ as it is revealed in the Scriptures and confessed in the Lutheran confessional writings.<br>
The Office of the Keys is less than faithfully exercised when admission to the Sacrament is granted to all who come to the altar regardless of their faith and congregational and/or denominational affiliation.The practice of open Communion renders it difficult,if not impossible,for church discipline to be exercised in a way that honors the ministrations being carried out by those to whom the responsibility of spiritual care for a member of God’s flock has been entrusted.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You can download the full document in PDF format from here:<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.lcms.org/belief/whatabout/wa_fellowship-lordssupper.pdf" target="top">www.lcms.org/belief/whatabout/wa_fellowship-lordssupper.pdf</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
