<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Consubstantiation rests on the same philosophical assumptions as the medieval doctrine of transubstantiation, which it opposed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
why did the need grow to define the differences (which seem minute to me) so explicitly?  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Both agree that, in the Eucharist, the accidents of the bread and wine remain unchanged. Unlike the doctrine of transubstantiation, however, that of consubstantiation asserts that the substance of the bread and wine is also unchanged, the ubiquitous body of Christ coexisting &quot;in, with, and under&quot; the substance of the bread, and the blood of Christ in, with, and under the wine, by the power of the Word of God.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
To my thinking, there is only an imagined line separating these two beliefs, consubstantiation and transubstantiation.  All living things are OF God, these things flow from the uncreated into the created.  What value does saying 'God transforms these elements INTO Christ' vs. 'These elements, the bread and wine, CONTAIN Christ, &quot;in, with and under&quot;' ?<br>
<br>
I mean no disrespect to various denominations by that, it just seems like an unnecessary conflict to me. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :thk --><img src=http://heartjoys.fcpages.com/Sparrow'sHearth/thk.gif ALT=":thk"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    ..but sometimes my bulb's not too bright either....<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
